{
    "level": "A1",
    "intro": "In questions with <strong>to be</strong>, the form <strong>am / is / are</strong> goes <strong>before the subject</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "Am I...?",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "Start the question with <strong>am</strong> when the subject is <strong>I</strong>.",
            "example": "Am I late?"
        },
        {
            "label": "Is he / she / it...?",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "With <strong>he / she / it</strong>, put <strong>is</strong> before the subject.",
            "example": "Is she at home?"
        },
        {
            "label": "Are you / we / they...?",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "With <strong>you / we / they</strong>, put <strong>are</strong> before the subject.",
            "example": "Are they ready?"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Basic question patterns",
    "intro": "Questions with to be do not use do / does.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "I",
            "title": "Am I ...?",
            "subtitle": "Am I early?"
        },
        {
            "label": "He / She / It",
            "title": "Is he / she / it ...?",
            "subtitle": "Is he busy? / Is it cold?"
        },
        {
            "label": "You / We / They",
            "title": "Are you / we / they ...?",
            "subtitle": "Are we late? / Are they at school?"
        },
        {
            "label": "Short Answers",
            "title": "Yes, ... am / is / are.",
            "subtitle": "Yes, I am. / No, he isn't. / Yes, they are."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. How to answer shortly",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Yes",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "In a short positive answer, repeat the form <strong>am / is / are</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Are you tired? — Yes, I am.",
                    "ua": "Are you tired? — Yes, I am."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Is she here? — Yes, she is.",
                    "ua": "Is she here? — Yes, she is."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "No",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "In a short negative answer, the short forms <strong>isn't / aren't</strong> are common.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Is he busy? — No, he isn't.",
                    "ua": "Is he busy? — No, he isn't."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Are they at home? — No, they aren't.",
                    "ua": "Are they at home? — No, they aren't."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Word order",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "Compare the statement and the question: the form of <strong>to be</strong> moves before the subject.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "She is ready. → Is she ready?",
                    "ua": "Inversion with to be."
                },
                {
                    "en": "They are at school. → Are they at school?",
                    "ua": "No do / does."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Question and short answer",
    "intro": "In the answer, you do not need to repeat the full sentence: a short form is enough.",
    "rows": [
        {
            "en": "Am I late?",
            "ua": "Yes, you are. / No, you aren't.",
            "note": "For Am I...?, the reply often uses you are / you aren't."
        },
        {
            "en": "Is she your teacher?",
            "ua": "Yes, she is. / No, she isn't.",
            "note": "is → she is / she isn't"
        },
        {
            "en": "Are they ready?",
            "ua": "Yes, they are. / No, they aren't.",
            "note": "are → they are / they aren't"
        }
    ],
    "warning": "📌 Do not say <strong>Do they are...?</strong> or <strong>Yes, they do.</strong>"
}

{
    "title": "4. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Keeping statement word order in the question.",
            "wrong": "❌ She is ready?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Is she ready?</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Adding do / does to to be.",
            "wrong": "❌ Do they are at home?",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Are they at home?</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Giving a short answer with do.",
            "wrong": "❌ Yes, she does.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">Yes, she is.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "5. Short summary",
    "items": [
        "Question with <strong>to be</strong> = <strong>am / is / are + subject</strong>.",
        "With <strong>I</strong>, start with <strong>Am I...?</strong>",
        "With <strong>he / she / it</strong>, start with <strong>Is...?</strong>",
        "With <strong>you / we / they</strong>, start with <strong>Are...?</strong>",
        "In short answers, repeat the form of <strong>to be</strong>: <strong>Yes, I am. / No, he isn't.</strong>"
    ]
}

